Add ivars that are present in ActiveRecord::TestFixtures to ManagesTransactions

These ivars are normally initialized by `setup_fixtures`, which isn't actually mixed into
cypress-rails, because we're piggy-backing on AR's fixture transaction management
feature, not actually using fixtures. As a result, this was probably never actually working
correctly for applications that spun up >1 connection in their test runs.

However, because we bind the connection pool call to self, this should at least get that
much working, though without a reproducible test case my confidence that this ever
worked as imagined or will start working now is very low. Nevertheless, should clear
the error being experienced without impacting anyone for whom this actually is
working as intended somehow.

Verified these ivars are present thru Rails 6.1.4

Remove references to the community edition

Improve and test JSON behavior in error scenarios

Failures in Cypress hooks (before, beforeEach, after and afterEach)
can't be accurately represented in JSON reports, there just isn't AFAIK
a good way to generate such report.

Before and After hooks are now no longer implemented using Cypress'
hooks. This ensures that we can properly generate reports in case of
failures in those.

The new behavor of these hooks are in line with how cucumber-js works,
but *not* how Cypress' hooks work. This surely warrants some
documentation...
Add an omitFiltered option, similar to that of cypress-grep
Move tag related features into a single directory

Remove ../methods postfix

This is now possible.

Retain generic properties of exported types of Cucumber methods

These were lost when consuming the original methods the way we did.
Furthermore, Before() & After() was exported as defineBefore() and
defineAfter().
Make sure to export DataTable type as well
Test and document how to replicate setWorldConstructor
Add attach(), similar to that from cucumber-js

Leverage the browser field

This makes usage a tad bit easier.

Filter specs in addCucumberPreprocessorPlugin()

This removes the need for `cypress-tags` altogether. Method inspired by
cypress-grep [1].

fix: add e2e target if it does not exists

CLI v12 does not generate the "e2e" target anymore.
With this commit, the schematic adds the target if it does not exist.

chore: remove node 10.x support

CLI v12 no longer supports it.

fix(schematics): use JSON schema draft-07

Angular CLI v12 now only supports JSON schema draft-07, meaning `id` needs to be renamed `$id`.
See https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/pull/20482 for more details.

Using the current schematics currently warns:

   "BriebugSchematicsCypress" schema is using the keyword "id" which its support is deprecated. Use "$id" for schema ID.

This commit updates the schema according to the breaking change.
switched chrome headless to chrome in sandbox karma conf
fix: use cypress types in generated tsconfig

fix: cypress as a dev dependency

Moves `cypress` from deps to devDeps, allowing users to set the version of Cypress they want to use in their package.json (without having to rely on a Yarn resolution to force the version).

Currently, as `cypress` is a dependency, even setting the version to `7.1.0` for example will still use the latest 6.x version installed by the schematic. With this fix, it should use the version specified in the package.json
fix(builders): base url not passed to cypress

fix: remove ts preprocessor

Cypress v4.4+ supports TS out of the box, removing the need for the preprocessor.

chore: add sandbox test in ci build

The CI currently does not run the sandbox test, making it hard to gauge if a PR is breaking something.
This commit updates the CI config to run these tests

Handle edge cases around empty results (#291)

In my usage of this plugin, I've come across an issue where cy.react returns an array of empty (null or undefined) value(s). This is happening on a page where the component I'm querying for will not render until a certain threshold of data is loaded into the application. The behavior I expect is that cy.react keeps retrying until the element renders (or until timeout), but in practice, I find that it doesn't retry once, but it immediately returns an array of `undefined`. I suspect that there is an interim state where the component exists in the virtual dom (thus resq can find it), but has not yet been rendered to the dom.

These changes, tested against the application I'm working on, handle this case and allow the plugin to know to retry.

Merge pull request #21 from StefanBruens/master

Cleanup of autovector interrupt code

Avoid multiple evaluation of argument to RESETTOGGLE macro

If the argument evaluation has side effects, the expansion has unwanted
effects. Also the evaluation may be expensive (e.g. fetching data from
a volatile register).
The new code can be better optimized by sdcc, and avoids fetching contents
from the volatile TOGCTL register.

replace USB/GPIF autovector asm code with normal interrupt

The jump table is target for both the USB as the GPIF interrupt. Including
autovector.h references the _gpif_isr/_usb_isr symbols and forces linking
of the jump table.

Signed-off-by: Stefan Brüns <stefan.bruens@rwth-aachen.de>

cleanup interrupt code

Autovector interrupts should not specify an interrupt number, as these
creates unnecessary entries in the interrupt table, wasting 8 bytes
of direct adressable memory per entry.
The entry for interrupt 13 (which is nonexistant) is used to reserve
enough space for the overlays for interrupt 8 (USB) and 10 (GPIF).

Signed-off-by: Stefan Brüns <stefan.bruens@rwth-aachen.de>

fx2.format: allow configurable fill in flatten_data().
Add definitions for USB high speed transaction per microframe count.
software: fix check for prebuilt bootloader.
Work around a bug in SDCC 3.5.
fx2.format: emit record type 04 (Extended Linear Address).
fx2queue: fix a bunch of macro hygiene issues.
Add a novel interrupt-safe queue implementation.

Fix unbalanced stack in delay_us_overhead() in case of early return.

Also, mark all delay functions as reentrant instead of messing with
the callee_saves pragma. It's cleaner and they're all naked anyway.

Incorporate even better nop optimization by 8051Enthusiast.

Optimize every last nop into total and utter oblivion.

Fix compatibility with ancient sdcc.

Which we use on our CI.

Fix bswap16 to return correct result.

Also, use optimal exchange sequence for both bswap16 and bswap32.
The debug serial port actually works at 230400 at 48 MHz core clock.
Don't require underscores in templated implementations.
Add a TX-only asynchronous serial port bitbang implementation.

Reimplement delay routines in cycle-accurate assembly.

Also, allow factoring caller overhead into delay cycle count.
Define ASM_GET_PARM for both 1- and 2-byte parameters.

Fix I2C behavior on bus contention.

This wasn't tested before; the hardware behavior is that STOP is not
cleared after BERR is set, presumably because by that point the FX2
I2C bus is tristated and so it can't emit a bus contention.

Fix running with `cypress open`

When in cypress open mode (interactive), we need to set
experimentalInteractiveRunEvents=true in config to have before:spec and
after:spec events to fire. Once opting in, we were getting an error on
after:spec because in interactive mode, the after:spec isn't called with
any results. We can simply presence-check things to avoid the error.

Remove retried snapshots before sending to happo.io

Fix filtering out passed snapshots

I made a mistake in an earlier commit to return from inside the
for-loop.

Add some debug logs to new code

To make it easier to debug things, I'm adding a few logs that show up if
you run with HAPPO_DEBUG=true

Allow cypress CI default run to retry once

This will make sure that we test the new functionality that I just added
with removing snapshots for failed attempts.

Remove retried snapshots before sending to happo.io

If a test is automatically retried, happo would duplicate snapshots that
were part of the retry and add a counter suffix to the variant name,
e.g. "foo-bar-1".

To fix this, I've made us listen to the after:spec event, then inspect
each test to look for failed attempts. If a failed attempt is found, we
delete all snapshots made during the duration of the failed attempt. I'm
making the assumption that timestamps will be in sync between the
browser process and the background node process. This could be
dangerous, but I couldn't find a better alternative to associate
snapshots with a test attempt.

Because of the added after:snapshot event handler, I'm changing the
initialization process:

happoTask.register(on)

This is a breaking change, so in order to help people upgrading without
updating config, I'm adding an assertion and an error message if we
detect that we haven't registered correctly.

Prevent resolving "undefined" after sha

In my previous fix for workflow_dispatch type events from github
actions, I accidentally made the after sha equal to `undefined`. This
eventually propagated to happo.io and made the report have id
"undefined".

After investigating workflow_dispatch events some more I found that the
event itself doesn't have the current sha. But there is a GITHUB_SHA
environment variable that we can look at.

While I was at it, I made the `link` work as well by constructing a link
to the commit in the github repo.

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Update copyright notices in all files

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Fix compiler warnings in beaglelogic_tcp.c

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Close device after detection, and reopen upon open

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Changes for proper operation in PulseView

Set samplelimit to a sane value (was causing PulseView to
crash earlier), as well as advertise samplerate using SR_CONF_LIST
so that PulseView can show the sample rates.

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Fix PulseView crash on close

Use dev_clear instead of std_dev_clear to clean up our private
data structure.

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Add beaglelogic_tcp_drain function

The function drains off all the remaining data in the receive socket
and is triggered before starting a capture and after a capture is
completed. In the absence of this function, there is a possibility of
data corruption and also the NodeJS TCP server throws an error if the
buffer is not completely read out before the socket is closed.

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Implement TCP protocol

BeagleLogic now supports two modes of interface - one being the
native mode running on an ARM system like the BeagleBone Black
and the other mode acting like a TCP client for the BeagleLogic
server running off a BeagleBone compatible system. This makes it
convenient for desktop users to retrieve samples from BeagleLogic,
no more copying files and SSHing into the BeagleBone hardware in
order to use BeagleLogic.

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Re-organize to prepare for TCP support

Organize driver functions into an ops structure (there will be
separate structures for both native and TCP mode of operation).

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Split beaglelogic code into .h and .c file

The code earlier was in a single .h file, so it's now separated into a C file
and H file

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Flexible sampleunit depending on enabled channels

If a channel in the higher-than-8-bit group is enabled then use
16-bit captures. Otherwise just do 8-bit captures.

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Remove 'as root' from warning message

Starting with Linux kernel version 4.9, BeagleLogic attributes
setting does not require root permissions.

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Enable seamless continuous capturing

This is done by setting triggerflags to 1 unless SR_CONF_LIMIT_SAMPLES is set

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

beaglelogic: Update scan() to return all 14 channels by default

This is unlike the previous behavior to return 8 channels and then
use logic_channels to get all the 14 channels

Signed-off-by: Kumar Abhishek <abhishek@theembeddedkitchen.net>

strutil: Fix sr_parse_rational for integral parts between -0 and -1

Values like '-0.1' would be parsed as being positive, as the integral
type does not discern +0 and -0. Also allow values without leading
integral value, to match behaviour of strtod/sr_atof.

Drop libftdi 0.x support, require libftdi 1.x.

There were some issues when using libftdi 0.x recently that are fixed
when switching to libftdi 1.x (not really worth the effort to investigate).

libftdi 1.x has been around several years now and should be available
in most recent distros and OSes. For the rare cases where it is not,
it's easy enough to get it via backport packages, or build from source,
or sigrok users can just use our binary installers for most OSes.

This also "fixes"/obsoletes bug #959.
